Recently, when I first lay down, there is a wave of negative energy that I have to ground myself through and see past. It comes in the form of chaotic intrusive thoughts. It gets more intense as I go into an in-between state, where I am not conscious at all, even though I am awake and aware of my unconsciousness. I sometimes pull myself out of it when I become aware of it. Sometimes just past this state, where I am more calm and grounded, I can observe my subconscious thoughts. They take the form of very fast-moving scenes that are bright and I know what they are, but they have no distinct shape that represents real life. hypna_example: It starts with a feeling of soft floating, as if you were suspended in the serene, azure waters of the cove.  Like the brilliant hues of the sunset sky, the day's discussions and chores start to lose their distinct edges.  I might find myself creating intricate patterns with the little, darting fish in place of a to-do list, their movements turning into a sophisticated, flowing dance.   The voices of the folks I spoke to that day echoed the calming rhythm of the waves, and their faces changed and evolved.  However, I concentrate on the underlying feelings-a sense of connection, a moment of humor, a shared challenge-rather than the exact words they used. These emotions turn into the warm, golden light that permeates the scene.The imagery also melds with my physical sensations.  The smooth, giving feel of the milky white sand replaces the sense of my head resting on the cushion.  The blanket's light pressure turns into warm, calm air that has a subtle hint of salt and tropical flowers in it.   My thoughts start to sound more like dreams and less like a straight line.  Even though I'm preparing the presentation for tomorrow, I'm visualizing a group of vibrant starfish listening to me explain it, their arms indicating agreement as I talk.  Or I'm working on a challenging subject at work, and the answer appears to me like a secret path that the ebbing tide has unveiled.It's like looking at the world from a peaceful distance, both present and detached.  Before I'm eventually swept away by sleep, the lines separating my body, my thoughts, and the outside world start to blur, leaving me with a sense of tranquil blending and silent surrender to the flow of consciousness.

routine: This isn't an intentional ritual, but I have noticed that if I'm reading a book or watching a video late into the night, I'm much more likely to "accidentally" fall asleep (as opposed to intentionally closing my eyes and waiting to fall asleep). This is a hypothesis based on experience, but here's what I think the explanation is: sometimes my brain "needs" (or thinks it needs) certain levels of stimulation (maybe that's part of my ADHD?). If I have nothing to think about while falling asleep, I've noticed that sometimes my mind will actively try to invent things to think about, and that mental activity ends up distracting me from actually sleeping. But if I'm reading or watching something that provides that stimulation, my mind can passively absorb it rather than needing to actively generate it, and so my mind can be less active, and thus more easily transition to sleep.
feedback: Especially when it comes to the vividness and detail of something I imagine, and the same for when I'm dreaming or falling asleep, I can "summon up" almost any detail I want, but everything other than that is extremely vague. I can jump between them quite quickly-with the lake landscape, for example, if I force myself to picture the entire scene, I get landscape contours but not much else; but when "just thinking about it," I find myself rapidly "zooming in and out" to different scales, to look at just the tree, then just the shape of the lake with no color or detail, then the surface of the lake with color and texture, then back out. At each level, I can only "see"that level-looking at the lake surface, I lose a sense of the lake's shape, and looking at the entire lake, I lose the sense of its color and texture. It's the same while I'm falling asleep: each detail that is "relevant" to what I'm thinking about is pretty clear, but everything else is extremely indistinct.

feedback: I have recurrent, vivid dreams of the significant places in my life (i.e. my undergraduate campus, or familiar streets and intersections) . Although these places are skewed in my dreams, these places look the same ,albeit skewed every time I dream of them. I could, at this moment draw a basic map of the places I repeatedly go in my dream. There is one intersection where I'm driving but I can't open my eyes - same intersection, same sensation every time. When my children were small I would be getting them dressed, ready for school, but then glance at a corner of the room and realize I was dreaming. Sometimes dreams are so real that I will stare at a wall or a car and force it to be a different color or pattern to test if I'm dreaming. I have had dream that were so vivid and realistic that I try to cover my ears and scream (I literally call them 'scream dreams'). Because I'm trying to scream, I will wake up  squeaking. I could not stay awake in school I would cram the night before an exam but set my alarm for 10 minute naps. During the exam I could remember the words on the pages I had read the night before as though the book was in front of me. There have been many instances where I dreamed a viable solution for a vexing (awake) problem. My overall impression of my dreams is that my mind/memories are filed in labeled folders (house, kids, happiness, sadness). Whatever happens in daytime that is significant enough to remember or forget, has to be put in one of these 'files'. Dreams seem to be the process by which my memories and experiences are categorized so they can be placed in the 'relevant'  file.  I'm from a family of narcoleptics, sleepwalkers, and even sleep talkers (one family member sat up in bed very suddenly and said, "Hooray for the United States of America - leading developer of the Phillips-head screwdriver!", then they laid down again and had no memory of talking in their sleep.). My kids, my sisters and at least one of their kids, talk about our dreams all the time. My mother's father and his brothers and sisters were all vivid dreamers and sleepwalkers. I have started out in my car, headed for a particular shopping center only to wake up/find myself in my mother-in-law's driveway; it's the most common destination when I drive in that direction. If something is misplaced and my family insists that I was the last person to handle the item, I have to ask them what I was doing when I was headed the item. So if I was putting clothes in a drawer, I could open the drawer and find the library book/hair ties or whatever went missing. I know my narcolepsy started when I was in the 3rd grade. Until I was diagnosed and medicated, I felt like I had been trudging through mud in a complete fog my entire life.  Once I was taking stimulants it was as though a heavy curtain was drawn in my brain; I could remember books I had read, recall the citation for I legal case I'd handled years ago.  I will also mention that I have Hyper-mobile Ehler Danlos and have had syncopal episodes my entire life (teasing apart the cataplexy from the syncope was not easy). Droxidopa has changed my life. It is the first, best, only medication to control my syncope. Surprisingly, it hasn't had any effect - positive or negative - on my sleep.

More involuntary and abstract than a day dream, like I was asleep but my dreams merged with my environment. feedback: I guess I'd like to reiterate that the 'drifting off' point of sleep for me is my favourite point of sleep, I actually love it and find it really pleasant, sometimes fun, it isn't emotionally intense but does make me feel warm and uplifted in a sense. My thoughts become so abstract it feels like a warm and creative space to be. This is particularly significant for me because I suffer with extremely emotionally intense bad dreams, nightmares and flashback dreams when actually asleep. It's extremely rare that I ever remember 'happy dreams'. Sometimes my dreams disturb me to such an extent that I wake up in floods of tears or having a panic attack, and they felt so vivid that my mental peace can be disturbed for sometimes days. Maybe that's why I love the drifting off stage so much, because it's the only time I actually feel that I am able to enjoy my dreams. I still feel partially conscious/in control and they aren't structured like my nightmares are.

Abstract forms appear in the dark. The shape of the form changes. I can decide between looking at the forms as they change shape, or let think about things/images. The two are very distinct at first, but the boundary becomes less and less clear as the shapeshifting object becomes my thoughts. The speed at which the boundary blurs correlates with my degree of fatigue. I can interact with the abstract form through suggestive thoughts ("What if" thoughts). For example, if I assume the form is stable in space (i.e. it doesn't move in my field of view), it will be relatively stable, sometimes drifting but very slowly. If I instead think that the form is moving, it might move quite fast, even disappear and reappear elsewhere. If I decide to wander into my thoughts instead of looking at the shape, the shape typically disappear and reappear elsewhere, or I simply lose track of it. But as the form becomes one with my mental imagery, it takes the shape of concrete objects. It can be a close object such as a piece of tissue, a mug, the corner of a table, a metallic bar, a piece of clothes. Or it can be a background object like a landscape, a scenery, a scene with a certain lighting or colours. Here, again, I can influence what the shape will turn into through suggestions: "What if it was a mug?"; then it turns into a mug. I the case of objects, I can interact with them. I usually try to grab them, and if I feel it, the dream is starting. If it is a background image, I will be quickly surrounded and enter a dream in that scene. If I feel the scene is too dark, I try to suggest that it's daytime instead, and it often works. I the scene is too scary, I still have the option to wake myself up. During this whole process, I can stay conscious enough to do the suggestions, or I can just let whatever will happen happen. In the latter case, I have little memory of the falling asleep period, besides that I was quickly caught in a vivid dream scenario, and that everything probably happened the way it does when I do my suggestions, though potentially faster. Now, a few examples: if the object is close by, I usually try to suggest things I can grab, preferably with some texture I can touch and play with (rugged surfaces, textile, etc.), as this helps me to fall asleep quickly. If it is a scenery, I try to depict daytime. I like to suggest a mountain view as it makes me feel peaceful. Then, it might at least start with a mountain, but can quickly turn into something else.
feedback: I find it difficult to known at what point one can state that a mental image is as clear and vivid "as reality". When I close my eyes, within a few seconds, I can depict both blurry and clear pictures. The clear ones are as clear as if I were to briefly look at a picture. But I don't think I can say that it is as real as reality as I don't feel immersed as much as if I was really there. In fact, for me, what would be surely as realistic as real would be if the environment is stable, and I could walk around and look at different things or details. But my mental imageries are very much unstable. For the example of the lake, the shape of the trees and the lake could completely change from one second to the next. In the end, I think a parameter here I was uneasy about when comparing mental imagery and real-life experience is the stability of the environment and the level of details and ability to interact and explore the environment that comes with it

routine: Yes, I have a consistent bedtime ritual that helps me fall asleep. I dim the lights and avoid screens for at least 30 minutes before bed. I often listen to calming instrumental music or ambient sounds while lying down. Sometimes I mentally rehearse the next day's tasks or reflect on the day's events, which helps me feel more settled. This routine signals to my mind that it's time to transition into sleep.
hypna_example: When I'm trying to fall asleep, my mind often becomes very active. I tend to replay conversations from earlier in the day or mentally rehearse what I need to do tomorrow. Sometimes I create fictional scenarios to distract myself-like imagining a story or visualizing a peaceful place-but my thoughts often loop back to unresolved tasks or worries. The content can shift quickly: one moment I'm planning something, the next I'm picturing a surreal scene or hearing faint imagined sounds. Even when I try to relax, my thoughts feel intrusive and hard to control, which makes it difficult to fall asleep.
feedback: I appreciated the depth of the questionnaire, but I'd like to add that my experience of falling asleep is often shaped by insomnia. This means my mental content can feel more intense, prolonged, and sometimes intrusive. I frequently experience looping thoughts, strategic planning, and immersive fictional scenarios that blend with environmental sounds or surreal imagery. These patterns don't always fit neatly into the categories provided, especially when sleep onset is delayed or fragmented. I also find that emotional tone and cognitive control vary depending on how tired I am or how much stress I've carried into the night. I hope future versions of this study will include more nuance around sleep difficulties and their impact on mental content.

I feel partially aware, but my control over thoughts slowly fades as I drift into sleep.
feedback: Overall, I feel that the questionnaire covered my experience of falling asleep quite thoroughly. One small addition I would mention is that my mental content can vary depending on factors such as stress levels, workload during the day, or screen usage before bedtime. Apart from this variability, I believe the questions accurately captured the different forms, timing, and intensity of my mental experiences during the transition from wakefulness to sleep.

hypna_example: When I first go to bed I might think about the events of the day (conversations that I've had, particularly if they were heated or embarassing), I might plan the rest of my week or make mental notes of chores that need doing, I might ruminate on things that I am anxious about (e.g. family troubles, relationship troubles, financial troubles, running of a household, etc). At some point I will try to redirect my thoughts by actively engaging in fantasy. Usually romantic fantasy. I will typically fall asleep during this stage, but it can take me hours (and always has, since I was a child). If I don't drift off to sleep in the fantasy stage I might listen to music or an ASMR video on youtube and sometimes I will fall asleep during that instead of during the fantasy stage. I often wake up from nightmares, that are usually related to real events in my life (e.g. my parents' deaths, issues with my siblings) but sometimes they are imagined events (e.g. my partner or siblings dying, heated arguments with people that never happened, etc). Even though I may fall alseep during a fantasy I have chosen to avoid anxious thoughts, the anxious thoughts often make their way back to me while I am unconscious. Other times, I dream absolute nonsense that makes no sense. Other times, I have sexual dreams and wake up during these.

If I have plans the next day, I will often be making a list in my head of things I need to do and things that will happen. If I do not, I will often imagine scenarios in my head involving myself and fictional characters.
